An interfaith prayer service was held for the late Olubadan of Ibadan, Oba Saliu Adetunji, on Tuesday. Islamic cleric, Prof. Kamil Olosho of the Department of Islamic and Arabic Studies, University of Ibadan (UI), said death respects no one. The late 93-year-old first class traditional ruler passed away on January 2, 2022. The supplications, which took place at the palace, requested peace in the royal family and among residents of Ibadan. Olubadan-in-Council members including former Oyo Governor, Rashidi Ladoja, the Osi Olubadan, attended. Others were Chief Tajudeen Ajibola, Osi Balogun; Chief Amidu Ajibade, Ekaarun Olubadan, and Chief
Lateef Gbadamosi, Ashipa Balogun Olubadan. Olosho urged advised people to live humbly “because death is inevitable, irrespective of status and can come at anytime”. The scholar advised them to do the will of Allah as “everyone will give account of his/her stewardship on Earth before God”. The academic described Adetunji as accommodating and a lover of all, irrespective of religion, ethnic or social classes. Deputy Chief of Staff to Governor Seyi Makinde, Abdulmojeed Mogbonjubola, led other government functionaries. Apostle Joshua Akinyemiju, Christian Association of Nigeria (CAN) Chairman in Oyo also presided over separate prayers for the deceased.